Reproducibility

Kirin Patel

1/27/2020

Reproducibility is a fundamental portion of data science. Without reproducibility, the validity of a result cannot be proven, and thus, all efforts made when conducting experiments are made irrelevant.

For this assignment, I will be reproducting the experiment from David K. Smith, Car Datasets, with this dataset.

install.packages("magrittr")

Importing Data

data_url = url('https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/autos/imports-85.data')
cars = read.csv(data_url, header=FALSE)

Setting Headers

These headers were obtained from imports-85.names.

headers <- c('symboling','normalized-losses','make','fuel-type','aspiration','num-of-doors','body-style','drive-wheels','engine-location','wheel-base','length','width','height','curb-weight','engine-type','num-of-cylinders','engine-size','fuel-system','bore','stroke','compression-ratio','horsepower','peak-rpm','city-mpg','highway-mpg','price')
names(cars) <- headers

Plots

# Miles Per Gallon
qplot(cars$'city-mpg',
      xlab = 'Miles Per Gallon (City)',
      ylab = 'Count',
      binwidth = 2, 
      main = 'Frequency Histogram: Miles per Gallon (City)'
)

qplot(cars$'highway-mpg',
      xlab = 'Miles Per Gallon (Highway)',
      ylab = 'Count',
      binwidth = 2, 
      main = 'Frequency Histogram: Miles per Gallon (Highway)'
)

# Number of Cylinders
table(cars$'num-of-cylinders')

# Displacement
qplot(cars$'engine-size',
      xlab = 'Displacement',
      ylab = 'Count',
      binwidth = 20,
      main = 'Frequency Histogram: Displacement'
)

# Weight
qplot(cars$'curb-weight',
      xlab = 'Weight',
      ylab = 'Count',
      binwidth = 200,
      main = 'Frequency Histogram: Weight'
)

# Price
qplot(cars$price,
      xlab = 'Price',
      ylab = 'Count',
      main = 'Frequency Histogram: Price'
)

Bivariable Plots

ggplot(data = cars,
       aes(x = cars$'curb-weight', y = cars$'city-mpg')) +
       geom_point() +
       geom_smooth(method='lm') +
       xlab('Weight') +
       ylab('MPG') +
       ggtitle('Weight vs. MPG (City): Entire Sample'
)

ggplot(data = cars,
       aes(x = cars$'make', y = cars$'city-mpg')) +
       geom_boxplot() +
       xlab('Make') +
       ylab('MPG (City)') +
       ggtitle('MPG Comparison by Make'
)

Conclusion

Unfortunately, due to the differences between datasets, I am unable to replicate some of the more interesting visualizations that David has created. However, even with this limitation, the same conclusions that David made can be made with this dataset. As car weight and engine size (displacement) increase, the efficiency of the vehicle decreases.

For more detailed analysis of car manufaturer trends visit Davids article.
